result.execSummary:
On one or more charges, the deferred prosecution or sentencing agreement(s) on this case were fulfilled, and the charge(s) were dismissed.

The defendant Seth Collin Knudson was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case. One or more other charges in this case were dismissed. The dismissed charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Seth Collin Knudson is presumed innocent of the dismissed charges.

  • Seth Collin Knudson was found guilty of Battery [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(1).

Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant will enter into a Deferred Prosecution Agreement for a period of: 24 months
Supplement to Disposition (Restitution)
Supplement to Disposition (Restitution)
Restitution hearing on March 1, 2017 at 11:00 am.

Defendant Seth Collin Knudson in court with attorney Cole Daniel Ruby.  Chad A. Hendee appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
  Atty Hendee states plea agreement to Counts 1 & 3.  Count 2 to be dismissed.    Upon the defendant's plea and prior to adjudication, defendant will enter into a Deferred Prosecution Agreement for a period of:  24 months with conditions on Ct. 1.  Atty Hendee states that the parties are stipulating to $550 + surcharge of restitution amount and then the remaining amount is disputed by the defendant and asks for a restitution hearing be set.    State has complied with victim notification requirements.  Atty Ruby agrees.  Court questions the defendant.  Defendant agrees and enters a No Contest plea on Ct. 1 and a Guilty plea on Ct. 3.
  Court questions defendant regarding plea. Advises of Constitutional Rights and elements of the charge.  Court finds plea made knowingly, voluntarily & Intelligently.  Court relies on the information for a factual basis.  

BY THE COURT:  Court finds a sufficient factual basis to support the charges.  Court accepts defendant's plea; approves and signs the 24 month DPA with conditions on Ct. 1 and finds the defendant guilty of Ct. 3.
Ct. 2 to be dismissed.

Atty Hendee makes sentencing recommendations and asks the court to follow the joint recommendation.  Atty Hendee states that the defendant has showed proof of domestic abuse counseling and therefore, that is why the State is not asking for that as a condition.
Court has reviewed the victim impact statement.
Atty Ruby makes sentencing arguments and asks the court to follow the agreement.

BY THE COURT:  Ct. 1:  Court approves the 24 month DPA with conditions.

Ct. 3:  Withhold Sentence; 24 months Probation with conditions:
*20 days in the Marquette County Jail w/huber
  Report on or before March 3, 2017 by 7:00pm, clean & sober.
*May transfer to Chippewa County
*Electronic Monitoring allowed
*Credit = 4 days (if revoked)
*Court Costs = $243.00
*$100.00 Domestic Abuse Surcharge
*DNA Sample + $200.00 Surcharge
*Comply with any and all counseling and treatment as recommended by the Agent
*Restitution to the victim = $550.00 + $55.00 Surcharge = $605.00
*No contact with the victim S.N.

Ct. 2 to be dismissed.
Remainder of the Restitution disputed by the defendant will be determined at a Restitution Hearing that will be set by the court.

Atty Hendee asks that the bond be applied to the Resitution first and then held for possible future restitution that is owed after the restitution hearing.
Atty Ruby agrees.
BY THE COURT:  Cash bond to be applied to the victim and paid out by the COC office and the remainder of the cash bond is to be held until after the restitution hearing.  Restitution hearing scheduled for March 1, 2017 at 11:00 am.
